ant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Arden","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name, either from the district of Arden in Warwickshire or from Arden in Bredbury (Cheshire). The first placename is thought to be derived from a Celtic word meaning ‘high place’, cognate with <i>Ardennes</i>, the name of a forested region on the borders between northeastern France and eastern Belgium. The second derives from Old English <i>hēah</i> ‘high’ + <i>worthign</i> ‘enclosed settlement’."],"variants":[{"name":"Harden","meanings":["English: variant of   Arden   with prosthetic <i>H-</i>.","English: habitational name, either from Haredene Wood in East Tisbury (Wiltshire), or from Haredon (in Ugborough, Devon). The first placename probably derives from Old English <i>hara</i> ‘hare’ + <i>denu</i> ‘valley’. The second is from Old English <i>hara</i> + <i>dūn</i> ‘hare hill’.","English: variant of   Harding  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert de Arden was born in 1450, in England, United Kingdom. He married Ann Harold in 1493. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1517, in his hometown, at the age of 67."},"et":{"1450–1517":"1450–1517","1460–1520":"1460–1520","1506–1571":"1506–1571","1520":"1520","1450":"1450","1571":"1571","1460":"1460","1506":"1506","1517":"1517",", 1493":"1493","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England"},"fi":{"1450–1517":"1450–1517","1460–1520":"1460–1520","1506–1571":"1506–1571","1520":"1520","1450":"1450","1571":"1571","1460":"1460","1506":"1506","1517":"1517",", 1493":"1493","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England"},"fr":{"1450–1517":"1450–1517","1460–1520":"1460–1520","1506–1571":"1506–1571","1520":"1520","1450":"1450","1571":"1571","1460":"1460","1506":"1506","1517":"1517",", 1493":"1493","England":"Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Sussex, England":"Sussex, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Robert de Arden est né en 1450, à Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Il a épousé Ann Harold en 1493. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fils. Il est décédé en 1517, dans sa ville natale, à l’âge de 67 ans."},"de":{"1450–1517":"1450–1517","1460–1520":"1460–1520","1506–1571":"1506–1571","1520":"1520","1450":"1450","1571":"1571","1460":"1460","1506":"1506","1517":"1517",", 1493":"1493","England":"England, United Kingdom","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England","lifeSummary":"Robert de Arden wurde 1450 in England, United Kingdom geboren. Er hat 1493 Ann Harold geheiratet. Sie hatten mindestens 1 Sohn. Er starb 1517 im Alter von 67 Jahren in seinem Geburtsort."},"ht":{"1450–1517":"1450–1517","1460–1520":"1460–1520","1506–1571":"1506–1571","1520":"1520","1450":"1450","1571":"1571","1460":"1460","1506":"1506","1517":"1517",", 1493":"1493","Engla